    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">which can be optimized via gradient descent.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">However, there are three main limitations with this original proposal of GNN pointed out by <a href="https://arxiv.org/pdf/1812.08434.pdf" target="_self">this paper</a>:</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><ol><li class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">If the assumption of “fixed point” is relaxed, it is possible to leverage Multi-layer Perceptron to learn a more stable representation, and removing the iterative update process. This is because, in the original proposal, different iterations use the same parameters of the transition function f, while the different parameters in different layers of MLP allow for hierarchical feature extraction.</li><li class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">It cannot process edge information (e.g. different edges in a knowledge graph may indicate different relationship between nodes)</li><li class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Fixed point can discourage the diversification of node distribution, and thus may not be suitable for learning to represent nodes.</li></ol></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Several variants of GNN have been proposed to address the above issue. However, they are not covered as they are not the focus in this post.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><h4 class="mbr-section-subtitle mbr-fonts-style mb-4 display-5">DeepWalk</h4></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">DeepWalk is the first algorithm proposing node embedding learned in an unsupervised manner. It highly resembles word embedding in terms of the training process. The motivation is that the distribution of both nodes in a graph and words in a corpus follow a power law as shown in the following figure:</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="image3 cid-tt612oXwA9" id="image3-5" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-12 col-lg-9">
                <div class="image-wrapper"><div class="image_style" style="width:96%;"><picture><source sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px" srcset="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/format:webp/1*rnGJihGgZRNF_hPuRP9s4Q.png 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/format:webp/1*rnGJihGgZRNF_hPuRP9s4Q.png 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/format:webp/1*rnGJihGgZRNF_hPuRP9s4Q.png 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/format:webp/1*rnGJihGgZRNF_hPuRP9s4Q.png 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/format:webp/1*rnGJihGgZRNF_hPuRP9s4Q.png 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/format:webp/1*rnGJihGgZRNF_hPuRP9s4Q.png 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/format:webp/1*rnGJihGgZRNF_hPuRP9s4Q.png 1400w" type="image/webp"/><source data-testid="og" sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px" srcset="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/1*rnGJihGgZRNF_hPuRP9s4Q.png 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/1*rnGJihGgZRNF_hPuRP9s4Q.png 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/1*rnGJihGgZRNF_hPuRP9s4Q.png 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/1*rnGJihGgZRNF_hPuRP9s4Q.png 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/1*rnGJihGgZRNF_hPuRP9s4Q.png 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/1*rnGJihGgZRNF_hPuRP9s4Q.png 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1400/1*rnGJihGgZRNF_hPuRP9s4Q.png 1400w"/><img alt="" loading="lazy" role="presentation" src="https://miro.medium.com/max/700/1*rnGJihGgZRNF_hPuRP9s4Q.png"></picture></div><p class="mbr-description mbr-fonts-style mt-2 align-center display-12 text-muted" style="font-size:12px;"><a href="http://www.perozzi.net/publications/14_kdd_deepwalk.pdf" target="_self">http://www.perozzi.net/publications/14_kdd_deepwalk.pdf</a></p><br></div></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">The algorithm contains two steps:</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><ol><li class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Perform random walks on nodes in a graph to generate node sequences</li><li class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Run skip-gram to learn the embedding of each node based on the node sequences generated in step 1</li></ol></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">At each time step of the random walk, the next node is sampled uniformly from the neighbor of the previous node. Each sequence is then truncated into sub-sequences of length <em>2|w| + 1</em>, where w denotes the window size in skip-gram. If you are not familiar with skip-gram, <a href="https://medium.com/word-embedding-with-word2vec-and-fasttext-a209c1d3e12c" target="_self">my previous blog post</a> shall brief you how it works.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">In this paper, hierarchical softmax is applied to address the costly computation of softmax due to the huge number of nodes. To compute the softmax value of each of the individual output element, we must compute all the e^xk for all the element k.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="image3 cid-tt612oXwA9" id="image3-5" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-12 col-lg-9">
                <div class="image-wrapper"><div class="image_style" style="width:59%;"><picture><source sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 442px" srcset="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/format:webp/1*4jWul1Di9ub2HBhpEBfClA.png 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/format:webp/1*4jWul1Di9ub2HBhpEBfClA.png 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/format:webp/1*4jWul1Di9ub2HBhpEBfClA.png 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/format:webp/1*4jWul1Di9ub2HBhpEBfClA.png 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/format:webp/1*4jWul1Di9ub2HBhpEBfClA.png 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/format:webp/1*4jWul1Di9ub2HBhpEBfClA.png 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:884/format:webp/1*4jWul1Di9ub2HBhpEBfClA.png 884w" type="image/webp"/><source data-testid="og" sizes="(min-resolution: 4dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 4) and (max-width: 700px) 50vw, (min-resolution: 3dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 67vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 3) and (max-width: 700px) 65vw, (min-resolution: 2.5dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2.5) and (max-width: 700px) 80vw, (min-resolution: 2dppx) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, (-webkit-min-device-pixel-ratio: 2) and (max-width: 700px) 100vw, 442px" srcset="https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:640/1*4jWul1Di9ub2HBhpEBfClA.png 640w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:720/1*4jWul1Di9ub2HBhpEBfClA.png 720w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:750/1*4jWul1Di9ub2HBhpEBfClA.png 750w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:786/1*4jWul1Di9ub2HBhpEBfClA.png 786w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:828/1*4jWul1Di9ub2HBhpEBfClA.png 828w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:1100/1*4jWul1Di9ub2HBhpEBfClA.png 1100w, https://miro.medium.com/v2/resize:fit:884/1*4jWul1Di9ub2HBhpEBfClA.png 884w"/><img alt="" loading="lazy" role="presentation" src="https://miro.medium.com/max/442/1*4jWul1Di9ub2HBhpEBfClA.png"></picture></div><p class="mbr-description mbr-fonts-style mt-2 align-center display-12 text-muted" style="font-size:12px;">The definition of Softmax</p><br></div></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Therefore, the computation time is <em>O(|V|) </em>for the original softmax, where <em>V</em> denotes the set of vertices in the graph.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Hierarchical softmax utilizes a binary tree to deal with the problem. In this binary tree, all the leaves (v1, v2, … v8 in the above graph) are the vertices in the graph. In each of the inner node, there is a binary classifier to decide which path to choose. To compute the probability of a given vertex <em>v_k</em>, one simply compute the probability of each of the sub-path along the path from the root node to the leave <em>v_k</em>. Since the probability of each node’ children sums to 1, the property that the sum of the probability of all the vertices equals 1 still holds in the hierarchical softmax. The computation time for an element is now reduced to <em>O(log|V|) </em>as the longest path for a binary tree is bounded by <em>O(log(n)) </em>where <em>n</em> is the number of leaves.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="image3 cid-tt612oXwA9" id="image3-5" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px; background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
